{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628418"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:56:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:56:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17215"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17215"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9905"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74836"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9905"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17215"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60342"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1924"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23235"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74836"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset severe headache and confusion that began two hours ago. She has a history of poorly controlled hypertension and takes Amlodipine, but often forgets to take it. She has left-sided weakness affecting both her arm and leg (power 3/5). Her pupils are equal and reactive to light.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears drowsy with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 13 (E3, V4, M6). Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 210/115 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Subarachnoid haemorrhage","Intracerebral haemorrhage","Cerebral venous thrombosis","Ischaemic stroke"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of headache, focal neurological deficit, and altered mental status, along with markedly elevated blood pressure. These features are highly suggestive of intracerebral haemorrhage, particularly in the context of poorly controlled hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracerebral haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset headache, focal neurological deficits, and altered mental status. Hypertension is the most common risk factor, and patients often present with markedly elevated blood pressure. The rapid onset and severity of symptoms reflect the mass effect and increased intracranial pressure from the expanding haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubarachnoid haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a sudden thunderclap headache and meningism, but focal neurological deficits are less common unless there is associated intracerebral extension. Altered consciousness can occur but is usually either minimal or severe rather than the intermediate state seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIschaemic stroke\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar focal deficits but typically does not cause such severe headache or altered mental status unless there is significant mass effect from a large infarct. The severely elevated blood pressure also favours haemorrhage over ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral venous thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E has a more gradual onset over days, and while it can cause headache and focal deficits, the combination with altered mental status and severe hypertension would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic intracranial hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E affects young, overweight women and presents with chronic headache and papilloedema. Focal neurological deficits and the acute presentation would be atypical.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Focal neurological deficits with altered mental status should raise suspicion for intracranial haemorrhage.","Subarachnoid haemorrhage typically presents with thunderclap headache and meningism.","The combination of headache, focal deficits, and altered mental status is highly suggestive of intracerebral haemorrhage."],"references":["Bigal ME, Lipton RB. The differential diagnosis of chronic daily headaches: an algorithm-based approach. J Headache Pain. 2007 Oct;8(5):263-72. doi: 10.1007/s10194-007-0418-3. Epub 2007 Oct 23. PMID: 17955166; PMCID: PMC2793374","Ahmed F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. Br J Pain. 2012 Aug;6(3):124-32. doi: 10.1177/2049463712459691. PMID: 26516483; PMCID: PMC4590146","Rajashekar D, Liang JW. Intracerebral Hemorrhage. [Updated 2023 Feb 6]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553103/","Harriott AM, Karakaya F, Ayata C. Headache after ischemic stroke: A systematic review and meta-analysis. Neurology. 2020 Jan 7;94(1):e75-e86. doi: 10.1212/WNL.0000000000008591. Epub 2019 Nov 6. PMID: 31694924; PMCID: PMC7011689.","Xie X, Zhang Y, Kong Q, Huang H, Yu Z, Luo X, Qu W. Current Knowledge about Headaches Attributed to Ischemic Stroke: Changes from Structure to Function. Brain Sci. 2023 Jul 23;13(7):1117. doi: 10.3390/brainsci13071117. PMID: 37509047; PMCID: PMC10377604."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60342"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17215"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60342"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T16:37:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T16:37:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9905"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74836"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ